overnment Printing Office in Australia. It explores the struggles experienced by printers as they engaged in technological retraining, shortly before facing factory closure. Topics explored include spatial memory within oral history, gender-labour tensions, the rise of neoliberalism and the secret making of objects 'on the side'. This book will appeal to researchers in design and social history, labour history, material culture and gender studies. It is an accessible, richly argued text that will benefit students seeking to learn about the nature and erosion of blue-collar work and the history of printing as a craft.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aDeindustrializationxCase studiesxAustralia. 0aDeindustrializationzAustraliavCase studies. 0aPrinting industryxEmployeesxAustralia. 0aPrinting industryxHistoryx20th centuryxAustralia. 0aPrinting industryxTechnological innovationsxAustralia. 0aPrinting industryxTechnological innovations. 0aPrinting industryzAustraliaxEmployees. 0aPrinting industryzAustraliaxHistoryy20th century. 7aART / History / Contemporary (1945-).2bisacsh  aCrafts.  aDesign history.  aGender.  aLabour history.  aMaterial culture.  aPrinting.  aTechnologies.  adeindustrialisation.1 aAdams Stein, Jesse, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2017 eBook-Packagez978311128281740uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152610603240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526106032423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526106032/original  a978-3-11-128281-7  Manchester University Press 2017 eBook-Packageb2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles